        <body id="d4">

            <div1 type="letter" n="1" id="d5">
                <head>Letter from Adelaide E. Case to Charles N. Tenney, <date value="1862-02-09"
                        >February 9, 1862</date></head>

                <pb n="1" entity="DSSR_000000766_0059"/>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <name type="place">Mecca</name>
                        <date value="1862-02-09">Feb. 9th "62</date>
                        <lb/>
                    </dateline>

                    <salute>Dear Charlie,</salute>

                </opener>

                <p> How the mind will<lb/> wander, when alone, and what is<lb/> more natural, than
                    that it<lb/> should stray &ldquo;way off&rdquo; to dear, absent<lb/>
                    friends. But I am quite confident<lb/> that it is not Natural as it used<lb/> to
                    be but, one loved friend, <orig reg="engrosses">engro&longs;ses</orig><lb/>
                    the wandering thoughts of Addie. </p>

                <p> My darling Hal has at last<lb/> returned to his &ldquo;home and
                    friends&rdquo; </p>

                <p> Oh! dear Charlie, you <hi rend="underline">certainly</hi> can<lb/> not know our
                    joy at his return<lb/> but I fear you feel his absence <pb n="2"
                        entity="DSSR_000000766_0060"/> full as much as we do his presence.<lb/> I
                    know you <orig reg="miss">mi&longs;s</orig> him, and I<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">almost</hi> could wish him with you<lb/> for your sake </p>

                <p> I received your <hi rend="underline">dear</hi> letter, friday<lb/> I know not why
                    it was that I<lb/> wept while reading it. Laurie brought<lb/> it from the
                        office, <add place="inline" hand="h1">and</add> immediately I<lb/> hurried
                    to my room to read it.<lb/> Something, seemed to tell me that<lb/> my thoughts
                    would be to sacred while<lb/> reading it to be <orig reg="witnessed"
                        >witne&longs;sed</orig>, even<lb/> by my <hi rend="underline"
                    >sister</hi>. Darling, did you ever<lb/> weep tears of joy? I know <hi
                        rend="underline">I</hi> did while<lb/> reading your darling letter. Noble
                    youth!<lb/> How I thanked God, that there was<lb/> one, not ashamed to own me as
                    a friend </p>

                <p> Can you be happy in Addie's love?<lb/> Then my own darling, be happy.<lb/> For
                        I <orig reg="confess">confe&longs;s</orig>, dear Charles, what, to
                    man,<lb/> I never before <orig reg="confessed">confe&longs;sed</orig>,
                    &mdash; my love<lb/> A pure and fervent love it is incessant<lb/> as time
                    itself. How long I have felt <pb n="3" entity="DSSR_000000766_0061"/> and known
                    it I dare not own. For a<lb/> time, I strove to clothe it in the<lb/>
                    appellation's of &ldquo;sister's regard&rdquo; for you.<lb/> A
                    &ldquo;sisterly interest&rdquo; in your welfare. </p>

                <p> But Charlie, I found that I <hi rend="underline">do</hi><lb/> not do so. It was
                    too sacrilegious.<lb/> But I must not dwell on this subject<lb/> Dear Charlie,
                    cruelly as Col. Tyler in-<lb/>
                    <unclear/> That you, for my sake, darling do<lb/> nothing rash. you will not
                    will you?<lb/> You will not be offended will you?<lb/> I should so dread to have
                    you get into<lb/> a quarrel with him. </p>

                <p>I am glad that you are going to<lb/> write for the &ldquo;Democrat&rdquo;
                    Bye the by<lb/> the &ldquo;Democrat&rdquo; and
                    &ldquo;Chronicle&rdquo; are<lb/> all one now called by the name of<lb/>
                    the latter. I was very much disappoin<lb/> ted at your not coming home with<lb/>
                    Hal still I think your chances<lb/> are good. I <orig reg="guess"
                    >gue&longs;s</orig> you have been as<lb/> faithful to your post as any of
                    the<lb/> company. Laurie says she will<lb/>
                    <pb n="4" entity="DSSR_000000766_0062"/> answer your &ldquo;short
                    note&rdquo; and send in this </p>

                <p> I presume it will be<del hand="h1">sol</del><lb/> so long that I will<lb/> be
                    obliged to pay double<lb/> postage. Darling Charlie<lb/> you will excuse
                    this<lb/> short letter as Hallie<lb/> is going away to night<lb/> and he wishes
                    me to stop writing<lb/> and sing with him. I will write<lb/> again in a few days </p>

                <p> Remember me to the boys,<lb/> meanwhile accept the love and <orig reg="blessing"
                        >ble&longs;sing</orig>blessing<lb/> of your's forever </p>

                <closer>
                    <signed>Addie</signed>

                </closer>

            </div1>

        </body>


